 forms to promote reflection on domestic crisis and imperial decline in contemporary America. Jagoda then looks at digital media that are interactive, nonlinear, and dependent on connected audiences to show how recent approaches, such as those in the videogame Journey, open up space for participatory and improvisational thought. Contributing to fields as diverse as literary criticism, digital studies, media theory, and American studies, Network Aesthetics brilliantly demonstrates that, in today’s world, networks are something that can not only be known, but also felt, inhabited, and, crucially, transformed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAesthetics. 0aArtsxPhilosophy. 0aCognitive science. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  anetworks, connection, popular culture, decentralization, underworld, film, syriana, television, the wire, crisis, politics, social commentary, decline, media, interactive, audience, video games, journey, improvisation, reader response, american studies, literary criticism, digital, aesthetics, cognition, community, philosophy, alternate reality, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022634648940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226346656423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226346656/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles